{"title_page": "First Things", "text_new": "{{About|a religious journal|the book|Hadley Arkes}}\n{{for|philosophical term|First principles}}\n{{Infobox Magazine\n|title          = First Things\n|image_file     = FirstThingsCover.jpg\n|image_size     = \n|image_caption  = \n|editor         = [[R. R. Reno]]\n|frequency      = Monthly\n|category       = [[Religion]]\n|company        = [[Institute on Religion and Public Life]]\n|firstdate      = March 1990\n|country        = [[United States]]\n|based          = New York City\n|language       = [[English language|English]]\n|website        = {{URL|http://www.firstthings.com/|www.firstthings.com}}\n|issn           = 1047-5141\n}}\n\n'''''First Things''''' ('''''FT''''') is an [[ecumenism|ecumenical]] and [[conservatism|conservative]] religious journal aimed at \"advanc[ing] a religiously informed public philosophy for the ordering of society\".<ref name=\"firstthings.com\"/> The magazine, which focuses on [[theology]], [[liturgy]], [[church history]], [[history of religions|religious history]], [[culture]], [[education]], [[society]] and [[politics]], is inter-denominational and inter-religious, representing a broad intellectual tradition of [[Christianity|Christian]] and [[Judaism|Jewish]] critique of contemporary society. Published by the [[New York City|New York]]\u2013based [[Institute on Religion and Public Life]] (IRPL),<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.firstthings.com/ |title=First Things - America's Most Influential Journal of Religion & Public Life |work=First Things}}</ref> ''First Things'' is published monthly, except for bi-monthly issues covering June/July and August/September.\n\n''First Things'' was founded in March 1990 by [[Richard John Neuhaus]], a clergyman, intellectual, writer and activist. He started the journal, along with some long-time friends and collaborators, after his connection with the [[Rockford Institute]] was severed.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.firstthings.com/article/2009/03/christian-unity-beginning-again-again-15 |title=FIRST THINGS: A Journal of Religion, Culture, and Public Life<!-- Bot generated title --> |publisher=}}</ref>\n\nWith a circulation of approximately 30,000 copies, ''FT'' is considered to be influential in its articulation of a broad Christian [[Ecumenism]] and erudite [[social conservatism|social]] and political [[conservatism]]. [[George Weigel]], a long-time contributor and IRPL board member, wrote in ''[[Newsweek]]'' that, after its founding, the journal \"quickly became, under [Neuhaus's] leadership and inspiration, the most important vehicle for exploring the tangled web of religion and society in the English-speaking world.\"<ref>[http://www.newsweek.com/2009/01/09/richard-john-neuhaus-1936-2009.html \"Richard John Neuhaus, 1936\u20132009\"], [[George Weigel]], ''[[Newsweek]]'', Jan. 10, 2009.</ref> [[Ross Douthat]] wrote that, through ''FT'', Neuhaus demonstrated \"that it was possible to be an intellectually fulfilled Christian\".<ref>[http://rossdouthat.theatlantic.com/archives/2009/01/richard_john_neuhaus_rip.php \"Richard John Neuhaus, RIP\"], ''[[The Atlantic]]'' blog, [[Ross Douthat]], Jan. 8, 2009.</ref>\n\n==Editors and contributors==\nRichard John Neuhaus, the journal's [[editor-in-chief]] until his death in January 2009, wrote columns called \"The Public Square\" and \"While We're At It\". Three editors served under Neuhaus: James Nuechterlein, a Lutheran, from 1990 to 2004; Damon Linker, a Jew converted to Catholicism, from 2004 to 2005, when he left over disagreements with the editor-in-chief (he later published ''The Theocons'', a book very critical of Neuhaus);<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.patheos.com/blogs/cosmostheinlost/2015/05/06/just-another-atheist-jewish-catholic-an-interview-with-damon-linker/2/ |title=Just Another Atheist Jewish Catholic: An Interview With Damon Linker |first=Artur |last=Rosman |date=6 May 2015 |publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.theamericanconservative.com/dreher/damon-linker-faith-journey/ |title=Damon Linker\u2019s Faith Journey |publisher=}}</ref> [[Joseph Bottum (author)|Joseph Bottum]], a Catholic, from 2005 to 2009.\n\nAfter his death, Neuhaus was succeeded by Bottum,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.firstthings.com/about.php?title_link=masthead |title=First Things - About Us: Masthead |date=27 May 2009 |work=archive.org |accessdate=5 September 2016 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090527232425/http://www.firstthings.com/about.php?title_link=masthead |archivedate=27 May 2009 }}</ref> who had come back from ''[[The Weekly Standard]]''. Bottum served through October 2010, when he was forced out after a controversy about the future and the funding of the magazine, and Nuechterlein returned from retirement to become ''interim'' editor.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ncregister.com/daily-news/first-things-new-old-direction |title=First Things\u2019 New Old Direction |work=ncregister.com |accessdate=5 September 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.firstthings.com/masthead |title=About Us: Masthead - First Things |date=31 December 2010 |work=archive.org |accessdate=5 September 2016 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101231204345/http://www.firstthings.com/masthead |archivedate=31 December 2010 }}</ref> [[R. R. Reno]], a professor of theology at [[Creighton University]] who had been involved with the magazine for over a decade and was a Catholic convert from the [[Episcopal Church (United States)|Episcopal Church]], became the magazine's third editor in April 2011.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://communio.stblogs.org/index.php/2011/02/reno-new-editor-of-first-thing/ |title=Reno new editor of First Things - Communio |work=stblogs.org |accessdate=5 September 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.firstthings.com/web-exclusives/2011/01/trustworthy-guides |title=Trustworthy Guides - R. R. Reno |work=firstthings.com |accessdate=5 September 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.firstthings.com/web-exclusives/2011/04/first-things |title=First Things? - R. R. Reno |work=firstthings.com |accessdate=5 September 2016}}</ref> [[David Blum]], [[David P. Goldman]], [[David Mills (editor)|David Mills]], [[Midge Decter]] (''ad interim''), and Mark Bauerlein have all worked as executive or senior editors. At present there are two senior editors: Matthew Schmitz and Julia Yost. Schmitz and Yost married in January 2018.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/01/28/fashion/weddings/julia-yost-matthew-schmitz.html |title=Julia Yost, Matthew Schmitz |date=5 March 2018 |publisher= |via=NYTimes.com}}</ref>\n\nContributors usually represent traditional [[Catholic Church|Catholic]], [[Eastern Orthodox Church|Orthodox]], [[Anglicanism|Anglican]], [[Protestantism|Protestant]] (especially [[Lutheranism|Lutheran]], [[Methodism|Methodist]] and [[Presbyterianism|Presbyterian]]), and [[Judaism|Jewish]] viewpoints.\n\nFrequent contributors in the magazine's first year (1990) included Catholic jurist [[Mary Ann Glendon]] (later [[United States Ambassador to the Holy See]]), rabbi [[David Novak]], Catholic philosopher, diplomat, and author [[Michael Novak]], Lutheran-turned-Catholic historian Robert Louis Wilken, Catholic scholar and papal biographer [[George Weigel]], and Lutheran ethicist Gilbert Meilaender. Others appearing included [[Gary Bauer]], [[William Bennett]], [[Peter L. Berger]], [[David Brooks (journalist)|David Brooks]], [[Robertson Davies]], [[Avery Dulles]] (later [[Cardinal (Catholic Church)|Cardinal]]), [[Jean Bethke Elshtain]], [[Robert P. George]], [[Stanley Hauerwas]], [[David Horowitz]], [[Peter Leithart]], [[Martin E. Marty]], [[Ralph McInerny]], [[Mark Noll]], and [[Michael Wyschogrod]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.firstthings.com/issue_archive.php?offset=4 |title=Issues Archive |work=firstthings.com |accessdate=5 September 2016}}</ref>\n\nFrequent contributors in recent years have included many of those writers, as well as Mark Bauerlein, bishop [[Charles J. Chaput]], [[Mary Eberstadt]], [[Anthony M. Esolen]], [[Timothy George]], [[David Bentley Hart]], [[Peter Hitchens]], [[Wilfred M. McClay]], [[Robert Royal (author)|Robert Royal]], [[Roger Scruton]], [[Wesley J. Smith]], and [[Carl Trueman]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.firstthings.com/issue-archive |title=Issues Archive |work=First Things}}</ref>\n\nSince May 2017 [[Shalom Carmy]], an [[Orthodox Judaism|Orthodox]] [[rabbi]] teaching [[Jewish studies]] and [[philosophy]] at [[Yeshiva University]] (where he is Chair of [[Bible]] and [[Jewish philosophy]] at [[Yeshiva College (Yeshiva University)|Yeshiva College]] and an affiliated scholar at [[Benjamin N. Cardozo School of Law]]) as well as editor of ''[[Tradition (journal)|Tradition]]'', has written a regular column named ''[[Lithuanian Jews|Litvak]] at large''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.firstthings.com/article/2017/05/benedict-option |title=Benedict Option |last=Reno |publisher=}}</ref>\n\nThe magazine publishes articles every day in the \"Web Exclusives\" section of its website.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.firstthings.com/feature-archive |title=Web Exclusives |work=First Things}}</ref>\n\n===List of editors===\n'''Editor-in-chief'''\n*Richard John Neuhaus (1990\u20132009), Lutheran/Catholic\n\n'''Editors'''\n*James Nuechterlein (1990\u20132004), Lutheran\n*Damon Linker (2004\u20132005), Jewish/Catholic\n*Joseph Bottum (2005\u20132010), Catholic\n*James Nuechterlein (''ad interim'', 2010\u20132011), Lutheran\n*R. R. Reno (2011\u2013present), Catholic\n\n'''Executive/senior editors'''\n*David P. Goldman (2009\u20132010), Jewish\n*David Blum (2010), Catholic\n*David Mills (2011\u20132013), Catholic\n*Midge Decter (''ad interim'', 2013\u20132014), Jewish\n*Mark Bauerlein (2014\u20132019), Catholic\n*Matthew Schmitz (2017\u2013present), Catholic\n*Julia Yost (2017\u2013present), Catholic\n\n==Governance==\nThe journal is run by the board of the Institute on Religion and Public Life, which is chaired by Robert Louis Wilken (who also serves as its president) and whose members include, among others, [[Mary Ann Glendon]], [[Russell Hittinger]], [[David Novak]] (vice president), and [[George Weigel]], as of January 2018.<ref name=\"firstthings.com\">{{cite web |url=http://www.firstthings.com/masthead |title=Masthead |work=First Things}}</ref>\n\nAs briefly mentioned, similarly to Neuhaus, Wilken is a former Lutheran minister converted to the Catholic Church.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.firstthings.com/blogs/firstthoughts/2014/12/the-evangelical-catholic-tradition |title=The Evangelical Catholic Tradition - Mathew Block |work=firstthings.com |accessdate=5 September 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.chnetwork.org/journey-home/dr-robert-louis-wilken-former-lutheran-minister-journey-home-program/ |title=Dr. Robert Louis Wilken: Former Lutheran Minister - The Coming Home Network |work=chnetwork.org |accessdate=5 September 2016}}</ref> The pair first met at the [[Concordia University Texas|Lutheran Concordia College of Texas]] in 1953, became friends, graduated in 1955, and earned the [[Master of Divinity]] at [[Concordia Seminary]] in 1960.\n\nFormer members of the editorial board include neoconservatives [[Gertrude Himmelfarb]] and [[Peter L. Berger]], who resigned in November 1996 amid \"The End of Democracy?\" controversy,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.firstthings.com/article/1999/03/001-the-future-of-the-end-of-democracy |title=The Future of the End of Democracy - J. Budziszewski |work=firstthings.com |accessdate=5 September 2016}}</ref> and Methodist theologian [[Stanley Hauerwas]], who resigned in February 2002 in protest with the journal's stance on the [[War on Terror]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.firstthings.com/article/1996/11/001-the-end-of-democracy-the-judicial-usurpation-of-politics |title=The End of Democracy? The Judicial Usurpation of Politics - Various |work=firstthings.com |accessdate=5 September 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.weeklystandard.com/stanley-hauerwass-pacifism/article/2496 |title=Stanley Hauerwas's Pacifism |date=13 May 2002 |work=weeklystandard.com |accessdate=5 September 2016}}</ref> Both Berger, a Lutheran, and Hauerwas continued to publish articles in the journal also after their resignation from the editorial board.\n\nThe journal used to have an advisory council (appointed  by the institute board). In mid 2017 it included, among others, neoconservative writer [[Midge Decter]]; historian [[Wilfred M. McClay]]; philosophers [[Hadley Arkes]] and [[Robert P. George]]; political scientist Timothy Fuller; Christian theologians or biblicists Gary A. Anderson (Methodist), Thomas Sieger Derr (Congregationslist), [[Timothy George]] (Baptist), [[Terryl Givens]] (Mormon), [[Chad Hatfield]] (Eastern Orthodox), [[Robert Jenson]] (Lutheran), [[Peter Leithart]] (Presbyterian), [[Cornelius Plantinga]] (Dutch Reformed), and Ephraim Radner (Anglican); Jewish scholars [[David G. Dalin]] and Eric Cohen, founding editor of ''[[The New Atlantis (journal)|The New Atlantis]]''; physicist [[Stephen Barr]]; and [[Mark C. Henrie]], president of the Arthur N. Rupe Foundation and former Chief Academic Officer and Senior Vice-President of the [[Intercollegiate Studies Institute]].<ref>https://rupefoundation.org/about/directors-and-officers//</ref><ref>https://home.isi.org/speakers-bureau-profile/2061/Mark%20Henrie</ref><ref name=\"masthead\">{{cite web |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170127015041/http://www.firstthings.com/masthead |title=First Things Masthead |date=27 January 2017 |publisher=}}</ref> Until his death in February 2017, the council included also theologian and writer [[Michael Novak]],<ref name=\"masthead\" /> who, along with fellow Catholics Neuhaus and Weigel, was part of the so-called \"neoconservative trinity\", according to critics.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://books.google.it/books?id=H8butfwlk5gC&pg=PA93&lpg=PA93&dq=novak+weigel+neuhaus+neoconservative+trinity&source=bl&ots=rONe0ePQih&sig=ppEGOSodacWoemGO1eFmGHDr8As&hl=it&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiUvrfw5NXUAhXMJFAKHbGOCqIQ6AEINjAC#v=onepage&q=novak+weigel+neuhaus+neoconservative+trinity&f=false |title=Prospettiva \"neocon\": capitalismo, democrazia, valori nel mondo unipolare |first=Flavio |last=Felice |date=5 March 2018 |publisher=Rubbettino Editore |via=Google Books}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.culturewars.com/2010/Manhattan.htm |title=Culture Wars: Manhattan Declaration |website=www.culturewars.com}}</ref>\n\nFormer members of the council include [[Jean Bethke Elshtain]], [[Ernest Fortin]], [[Elizabeth Fox-Genovese]], [[Suzanne Garment]], [[Bruce C. Hafen]], [[Carl F. H. Henry]], Leonid Kishkovsky, [[Glenn Loury]], [[George Marsden]], Gilbert Meilaender (who still contributes to the journal), and [[Max Lynn Stackhouse]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://firstthings.com/menus/about.html |title=About First Things |date=12 April 1997 |work=archive.org |accessdate=5 September 2016 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/19970412182745/http://firstthings.com/menus/about.html |archivedate=12 April 1997 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://firstthings.com/menus/about.html |title=About First Things |date=9 January 1998 |work=archive.org |accessdate=5 September 2016 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/19980109142147/http://firstthings.com/menus/about.html |archivedate=9 January 1998 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.firstthings.com/ Official website]\n\n{{Intermediates between Catholicism and Protestantism}}\n{{Neoconservatism}}\n\n[[Category:American monthly magazines]]\n[[Category:American political magazines]]\n[[Category:American conservative magazines]]\n[[Category:Magazines established in 1990]]\n[[Category:American religious magazines]]\n[[Category:Christianity studies journals]]\n[[Category:Magazines published in New York City]]\n[[Category:Christian magazines]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|a religious journal|the book|Hadley Arkes}}\n{{for|philosophical term|First principles}}\n{{Infobox Magazine\n|title          = First Things\n|image_file     = FirstThingsCover.jpg\n|image_size     = \n|image_caption  = \n|editor         = [[R. R. Reno]]\n|frequency      = Monthly\n|category       = [[Religion]]\n|company        = [[Institute on Religion and Public Life]]\n|firstdate      = March 1990\n|country        = [[United States]]\n|based          = New York City\n|language       = [[English language|English]]\n|website        = {{URL|http://www.firstthings.com/|www.firstthings.com}}\n|issn           = 1047-5141\n}}\n\n'''''First Things''''' ('''''FT''''') is an [[ecumenism|ecumenical]] and [[conservatism|conservative]] religious journal aimed at \"advanc[ing] a religiously informed public philosophy for the ordering of society\".<ref name=\"firstthings.com\"/> The magazine, which focuses on [[theology]], [[liturgy]], [[church history]], [[history of religions|religious history]], [[culture]], [[education]], [[society]] and [[politics]], is inter-denominational and inter-religious, representing a broad intellectual tradition of [[Christianity|Christian]] and [[Judaism|Jewish]] critique of contemporary society. Published by the [[New York City|New York]]\u2013based [[Institute on Religion and Public Life]] (IRPL),<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.firstthings.com/ |title=First Things - America's Most Influential Journal of Religion & Public Life |work=First Things}}</ref> ''First Things'' is published monthly, except for bi-monthly issues covering June/July and August/September.\n\n''First Things'' was founded in March 1990 by [[Richard John Neuhaus]], a clergyman, intellectual, writer and activist. He started the journal, along with some long-time friends and collaborators, after his connection with the [[Rockford Institute]] was severed.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.firstthings.com/article/2009/03/christian-unity-beginning-again-again-15 |title=FIRST THINGS: A Journal of Religion, Culture, and Public Life<!-- Bot generated title --> |publisher=}}</ref>\n\nWith a circulation of approximately 30,000 copies, ''FT'' is considered to be influential in its articulation of a broad Christian [[Ecumenism]] and erudite [[social conservatism|social]] and political [[conservatism]]. [[George Weigel]], a long-time contributor and IRPL board member, wrote in ''[[Newsweek]]'' that, after its founding, the journal \"quickly became, under [Neuhaus's] leadership and inspiration, the most important vehicle for exploring the tangled web of religion and society in the English-speaking world.\"<ref>[http://www.newsweek.com/2009/01/09/richard-john-neuhaus-1936-2009.html \"Richard John Neuhaus, 1936\u20132009\"], [[George Weigel]], ''[[Newsweek]]'', Jan. 10, 2009.</ref> [[Ross Douthat]] wrote that, through ''FT'', Neuhaus demonstrated \"that it was possible to be an intellectually fulfilled Christian\".<ref>[http://rossdouthat.theatlantic.com/archives/2009/01/richard_john_neuhaus_rip.php \"Richard John Neuhaus, RIP\"], ''[[The Atlantic]]'' blog, [[Ross Douthat]], Jan. 8, 2009.</ref>\n\n==Editors and contributors==\nRichard John Neuhaus, the journal's [[editor-in-chief]] until his death in January 2009, wrote columns called \"The Public Square\" and \"While We're At It\". Three editors served under Neuhaus: James Nuechterlein, a Lutheran, from 1990 to 2004; Damon Linker, a Jew converted to Catholicism, from 2004 to 2005, when he left over disagreements with the editor-in-chief (he later published ''The Theocons'', a book very critical of Neuhaus);<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.patheos.com/blogs/cosmostheinlost/2015/05/06/just-another-atheist-jewish-catholic-an-interview-with-damon-linker/2/ |title=Just Another Atheist Jewish Catholic: An Interview With Damon Linker |first=Artur |last=Rosman |date=6 May 2015 |publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.theamericanconservative.com/dreher/damon-linker-faith-journey/ |title=Damon Linker\u2019s Faith Journey |publisher=}}</ref> [[Joseph Bottum (author)|Joseph Bottum]], a Catholic, from 2005 to 2009.\n\nAfter his death, Neuhaus was succeeded by Bottum,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.firstthings.com/about.php?title_link=masthead |title=First Things - About Us: Masthead |date=27 May 2009 |work=archive.org |accessdate=5 September 2016 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090527232425/http://www.firstthings.com/about.php?title_link=masthead |archivedate=27 May 2009 }}</ref> who had come back from ''[[The Weekly Standard]]''. Bottum served through October 2010, when he was forced out after a controversy about the future and the funding of the magazine, and Nuechterlein returned from retirement to become ''interim'' editor.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ncregister.com/daily-news/first-things-new-old-direction |title=First Things\u2019 New Old Direction |work=ncregister.com |accessdate=5 September 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.firstthings.com/masthead |title=About Us: Masthead - First Things |date=31 December 2010 |work=archive.org |accessdate=5 September 2016 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101231204345/http://www.firstthings.com/masthead |archivedate=31 December 2010 }}</ref> [[R. R. Reno]], a professor of theology at [[Creighton University]] who had been involved with the magazine for over a decade and was a Catholic convert from the [[Episcopal Church (United States)|Episcopal Church]], became the magazine's third editor in April 2011.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://communio.stblogs.org/index.php/2011/02/reno-new-editor-of-first-thing/ |title=Reno new editor of First Things - Communio |work=stblogs.org |accessdate=5 September 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.firstthings.com/web-exclusives/2011/01/trustworthy-guides |title=Trustworthy Guides - R. R. Reno |work=firstthings.com |accessdate=5 September 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.firstthings.com/web-exclusives/2011/04/first-things |title=First Things? - R. R. Reno |work=firstthings.com |accessdate=5 September 2016}}</ref> [[David Blum]], [[David P. Goldman]], [[David Mills (editor)|David Mills]], [[Midge Decter]] (''ad interim''), and Mark Bauerlein have all worked as executive or senior editors. At present there are two senior editors: Matthew Schmitz and Julia Yost. Schmitz and Yost married in January 2018.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/01/28/fashion/weddings/julia-yost-matthew-schmitz.html |title=Julia Yost, Matthew Schmitz |date=5 March 2018 |publisher= |via=NYTimes.com}}</ref>\n\nContributors usually represent traditional [[Catholic Church|Catholic]], [[Eastern Orthodox Church|Orthodox]], [[Anglicanism|Anglican]], [[Protestantism|Protestant]] (especially [[Lutheranism|Lutheran]], [[Methodism|Methodist]] and [[Presbyterianism|Presbyterian]]), and [[Judaism|Jewish]] viewpoints.\n\nFrequent contributors in the magazine's first year (1990) included Catholic jurist [[Mary Ann Glendon]] (later [[United States Ambassador to the Holy See]]), rabbi [[David Novak]], Catholic philosopher, diplomat, and author [[Michael Novak]], Lutheran-turned-Catholic historian Robert Louis Wilken, Catholic scholar and papal biographer [[George Weigel]], and Lutheran ethicist Gilbert Meilaender. Others appearing included [[Gary Bauer]], [[William Bennett]], [[Peter L. Berger]], [[David Brooks (journalist)|David Brooks]], [[Robertson Davies]], [[Avery Dulles]] (later [[Cardinal (Catholic Church)|Cardinal]]), [[Jean Bethke Elshtain]], [[Robert P. George]], [[Stanley Hauerwas]], [[David Horowitz]], [[Peter Leithart]], [[Martin E. Marty]], [[Ralph McInerny]], [[Mark Noll]], and [[Michael Wyschogrod]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.firstthings.com/issue_archive.php?offset=4 |title=Issues Archive |work=firstthings.com |accessdate=5 September 2016}}</ref>\n\nFrequent contributors in recent years have included many of those writers, as well as Mark Bauerlein, bishop [[Charles J. Chaput]], [[Mary Eberstadt]], [[Anthony M. Esolen]], [[Timothy George]], [[David Bentley Hart]], [[Peter Hitchens]], [[Wilfred M. McClay]], [[Robert Royal (author)|Robert Royal]], [[Roger Scruton]], [[Wesley J. Smith]], and [[Carl Trueman]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.firstthings.com/issue-archive |title=Issues Archive |work=First Things}}</ref>\n\nSince May 2017 [[Shalom Carmy]], an [[Orthodox Judaism|Orthodox]] [[rabbi]] teaching [[Jewish studies]] and [[philosophy]] at [[Yeshiva University]] (where he is Chair of [[Bible]] and [[Jewish philosophy]] at [[Yeshiva College (Yeshiva University)|Yeshiva College]] and an affiliated scholar at [[Benjamin N. Cardozo School of Law]]) as well as editor of ''[[Tradition (journal)|Tradition]]'', has written a regular column named ''[[Lithuanian Jews|Litvak]] at large''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.firstthings.com/article/2017/05/benedict-option |title=Benedict Option |last=Reno |publisher=}}</ref>\n\nThe magazine publishes articles every day in the \"Web Exclusives\" section of its website.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.firstthings.com/feature-archive |title=Web Exclusives |work=First Things}}</ref>\n\n===List of editors===\n'''Editor-in-chief'''\n*Richard John Neuhaus (1990\u20132009), Lutheran/Catholic\n\n'''Editors'''\n*James Nuechterlein (1990\u20132004), Lutheran\n*Damon Linker (2004\u20132005), Jewish/Catholic\n*Joseph Bottum (2005\u20132010), Catholic\n*James Nuechterlein (''ad interim'', 2010\u20132011), Lutheran\n*R. R. Reno (2011\u2013present), Catholic\n\n'''Executive/senior editors'''\n*David P. Goldman (2009\u20132010), Jewish\n*David Blum (2010), Catholic\n*David Mills (2011\u20132013), Catholic\n*Midge Decter (''ad interim'', 2013\u20132014), Jewish\n*Mark Bauerlein (2014\u20132019), Catholic\n*Matthew Schmitz (2017\u2013present), Catholic\n*Julia Yost (2017\u2013present), Catholic\n\n==Governance==\nThe journal is run by the board of the Institute on Religion and Public Life, which is chaired by Robert Louis Wilken (who also serves as its president) and whose members include, among others, [[Mary Ann Glendon]], [[Russell Hittinger]], [[David Novak]] (vice president), and [[George Weigel]], as of January 2018.<ref name=\"firstthings.com\">{{cite web |url=http://www.firstthings.com/masthead |title=Masthead |work=First Things}}</ref>\n\nAs briefly mentioned, similarly to Neuhaus, Wilken is a former Lutheran minister converted to the Catholic Church.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.firstthings.com/blogs/firstthoughts/2014/12/the-evangelical-catholic-tradition |title=The Evangelical Catholic Tradition - Mathew Block |work=firstthings.com |accessdate=5 September 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.chnetwork.org/journey-home/dr-robert-louis-wilken-former-lutheran-minister-journey-home-program/ |title=Dr. Robert Louis Wilken: Former Lutheran Minister - The Coming Home Network |work=chnetwork.org |accessdate=5 September 2016}}</ref> The pair first met at the [[Concordia University Texas|Lutheran Concordia College of Texas]] in 1953, became friends, graduated in 1955, and earned the [[Master of Divinity]] at [[Concordia Seminary]] in 1960.\n\nFormer members of the editorial board include neoconservatives [[Gertrude Himmelfarb]] and [[Peter L. Berger]], who resigned in November 1996 amid \"The End of Democracy?\" controversy,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.firstthings.com/article/1999/03/001-the-future-of-the-end-of-democracy |title=The Future of the End of Democracy - J. Budziszewski |work=firstthings.com |accessdate=5 September 2016}}</ref> and Methodist theologian [[Stanley Hauerwas]], who resigned in February 2002 in protest with the journal's stance on the [[War on Terror]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.firstthings.com/article/1996/11/001-the-end-of-democracy-the-judicial-usurpation-of-politics |title=The End of Democracy? The Judicial Usurpation of Politics - Various |work=firstthings.com |accessdate=5 September 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.weeklystandard.com/stanley-hauerwass-pacifism/article/2496 |title=Stanley Hauerwas's Pacifism |date=13 May 2002 |work=weeklystandard.com |accessdate=5 September 2016}}</ref> Both Berger, a Lutheran, and Hauerwas continued to publish articles in the journal also after their resignation from the editorial board.\n\nThe journal used to have an advisory council (appointed  by the institute board). In mid 2017 it included, among others, neoconservative writer [[Midge Decter]]; historian [[Wilfred M. McClay]]; philosophers [[Hadley Arkes]] and [[Robert P. George]]; political scientist Timothy Fuller; Christian theologians or biblicists Gary A. Anderson (Methodist), Thomas Sieger Derr (Congregationslist), [[Timothy George]] (Baptist), [[Terryl Givens]] (Mormon), [[Chad Hatfield]] (Eastern Orthodox), [[Robert Jenson]] (Lutheran), [[Peter Leithart]] (Presbyterian), [[Cornelius Plantinga]] (Dutch Reformed), and Ephraim Radner](Anglican); Jewish scholars [[David G. Dalin]] and Eric Cohen, founding editor of ''[[The New Atlantis (journal)|The New Atlantis]]''; physicist [[Stephen Barr]]; and [[Mark C. Henrie]], president of the Arthur N. Rupe Foundation and former Chief Academic Officer and Senior Vice-President of the [[Intercollegiate Studies Institute]].<ref>https://rupefoundation.org/about/directors-and-officers//</ref><ref>https://home.isi.org/speakers-bureau-profile/2061/Mark%20Henrie</ref><ref name=\"masthead\">{{cite web |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170127015041/http://www.firstthings.com/masthead |title=First Things Masthead |date=27 January 2017 |publisher=}}</ref> Until his death in February 2017, the council included also theologian and writer [[Michael Novak]],<ref name=\"masthead\" /> who, along with fellow Catholics Neuhaus and Weigel, was part of the so-called \"neoconservative trinity\", according to critics.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://books.google.it/books?id=H8butfwlk5gC&pg=PA93&lpg=PA93&dq=novak+weigel+neuhaus+neoconservative+trinity&source=bl&ots=rONe0ePQih&sig=ppEGOSodacWoemGO1eFmGHDr8As&hl=it&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiUvrfw5NXUAhXMJFAKHbGOCqIQ6AEINjAC#v=onepage&q=novak+weigel+neuhaus+neoconservative+trinity&f=false |title=Prospettiva \"neocon\": capitalismo, democrazia, valori nel mondo unipolare |first=Flavio |last=Felice |date=5 March 2018 |publisher=Rubbettino Editore |via=Google Books}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.culturewars.com/2010/Manhattan.htm |title=Culture Wars: Manhattan Declaration |website=www.culturewars.com}}</ref>\n\nFormer members of the council include [[Jean Bethke Elshtain]], [[Ernest Fortin]], [[Elizabeth Fox-Genovese]], [[Suzanne Garment]], [[Bruce C. Hafen]], [[Carl F. H. Henry]], Leonid Kishkovsky, [[Glenn Loury]], [[George Marsden]], Gilbert Meilaender (who still contributes to the journal), and [[Max Lynn Stackhouse]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://firstthings.com/menus/about.html |title=About First Things |date=12 April 1997 |work=archive.org |accessdate=5 September 2016 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/19970412182745/http://firstthings.com/menus/about.html |archivedate=12 April 1997 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://firstthings.com/menus/about.html |title=About First Things |date=9 January 1998 |work=archive.org |accessdate=5 September 2016 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/19980109142147/http://firstthings.com/menus/about.html |archivedate=9 January 1998 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.firstthings.com/ Official website]\n\n{{Intermediates between Catholicism and Protestantism}}\n{{Neoconservatism}}\n\n[[Category:American monthly magazines]]\n[[Category:American political magazines]]\n[[Category:American conservative magazines]]\n[[Category:Magazines established in 1990]]\n[[Category:American religious magazines]]\n[[Category:Christianity studies journals]]\n[[Category:Magazines published in New York City]]\n[[Category:Christian magazines]]\n", "name_user": "Genericusername57", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eGovernance:punct", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/First_Things"}
